  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is **absolutely prohibited** in virtually every country around the world. It is a serious crime with severe penalties, including imprisonment and significant fines.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Facilitates other crimes:** Money laundering allows criminals to profit from illegal activities such as drug trafficking, human trafficking, terrorism, and corruption.\n*   **Undermines financial systems:** It can destabilize financial institutions and damage the integrity of the financial system.\n*   **Distorts economies:** It can lead to inaccurate economic data and unfair competition.\n\nGovernments have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering, including:\n\n*   **Anti-Money Laundering (AML) laws:** These laws require financial institutions to implement measures to detect and prevent money laundering, such as customer due diligence, suspicious activity reporting, and record-keeping.\n*   **Counter-Terrorism Financing (CTF) laws:** These laws target the financing of terrorist activities, which often involves similar methods to money laundering.\n*   **International cooperation:** Countries cooperate through international organizations and agreements to share information and coordinate efforts to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nIn short, money laundering is a serious offense that is strictly prohibited and actively combatted worldwide.\n",
